observations.recommendation:
Inventory Committee to prepare the PIP for approval of the Local Chief Executive (LCE) and submit the same to the Audit Team at least ten calendar days before the scheduled start of inventory-taking activities;
Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all PPE following the guidelines outlined in COA Circular No. 2020-006 and submit the RPCPPE to the Audit Team; 

Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain Property Cards and PPELCs, respectively, and reconcile their PPE records;

Property Officer/Municipal Treasurer to prepare ARE upon issuance of property and equipment and ensure that details thereof are complete especially the serial numbers. Look into the records of all properties of the Agency and issue ARE thereof to the concerned officials and employees in possession of or are using the same. Moreover, ensure that these are renewed every three years pursuant to the existing regulations to safeguard government property from possible loss or misappropriation; and

Inventory Committee to exert utmost effort in conducting the activities relative to the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE direct the:

Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit the BRS on a monthly basis, together with the copies of the bank statements and supporting documents for the reconciling items, within the prescribed period for a timely review/verification of such report; 

Municipal Treasurer to facilitate the immediate transfer of the balance of the account maintained at PNB to an AGDB, and to close accounts that have become dormant and revert back to the Source Agency or the Bureau of the Treasury, as the case maybe; 

Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain cashbooks for every Cash in Bank account maintained by the LGU and to reconcile the balances thereof with the subsidiary ledgers maintained by the Accounting Office.

We recommended that the LCE institutionalize the PSCP by creating a working group that will perform the following activities to: 

a. Conduct risk assessment;
b. Identify critical processes and functions; 
c. Determine scenarios that may disrupt normal operation; 
d. Conduct risk analysis and impact analysis;
e. Formulate the PSCP based on the identified risks on critical processes and functions and its related steps to be followed to eliminate, if not mitigate, the impact of the determined disruptions following the prescribed template and be guided by the PSCP guidebook; and
f. Submit plan to the MDRRMO for review, to the LCE for approval, and to the Sangguniang Bayan for the passage of a resolution to institutionalize the PSCP. 

Further, we recommended that members of the working group be capacitated by allowing them to attend seminars/trainings on the formulation of the PSCP.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to facilitate the conduct of complete physical count of all the Municipality’s properties annually and prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Office of the Auditor;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to prepare and maintain property records for all PPE and undertake the required reconciliation of the Property and Accounting records thereafter;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments to come up with the correct PPE accounts balances; and
Facilitate the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances through the implementation of COA Circular No. 2020-006.

We recommended that the LCE:
Require the Municipal Treasurer, the Liquidating Officer and the Collectors, by issuing demand letters, to deposit/turnover immediately their undeposited/unremitted collections and submit the copies of the Report of Collection and Deposits (RCD), Report of Collections and Remittances (RCRs) and deposit slips to the Office of the Auditor;
Stop the practice of utilizing the collections for the payment of contractors and other borrowings. Discuss during regular meetings that vales or IOUs from the Municipal Treasurer, Liquidating Officer or collectors must be prohibited and give emphasis that the vales or IOUs are disallowed in audit;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the difference in the balance of the Cash-Local Treasury account between their Offices, submit their working papers/reconciliation documents to the Office of the Auditor, and prepare necessary correcting entries in the Agency’s books or cashbooks;
Direct the Municipal Treasurer, the Liquidating Officers and the collectors to deposit/turnover all subsequent collections intact and not to retain portion of them; and
Strengthen internal control over collections, remittances and deposits to avoid retention of big amounts of money in the hands of the accountable officers and consider the promulgation and implementation of a policy on the following:
Verification by the Liquidating Officer of the unused accountable forms in the possession of collectors upon remittance to ensure that all collections are remitted daily and intact; and
Limitations in the issuance of receipts to the collectors, including the non-issuance of new stubs of receipts to those with unremitted collections.

We recommended that Management:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct an actual physical inventory count of all the local roads and prepare and submit the RPCLRN;
Require the Municipal Engineer to provide the Inventory Committee with complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects to facilitate the preparation of RPCLRN;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and maintain separate SLs/LRNLCs and LRNPCs, respectively, for local road projects and reconcile both records to ensure proper recording and control of the assets;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare and submit the RLRN and Local Road Inventory and Road Map; and
Require the Municipal Accountant to prepare a lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component of road network and provide proper and complete disclosure of the total road networks in the Notes to FS in accordance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2015-008.

We recommended that the LCE:
Enjoin the LDRRM Office to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of disaster risk reduction and management towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities. Closely monitor the implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate corrective action, if any, and the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization;
Require the Municipal Accountant that reconciliation between the Report on Utilization of LDRRMF and disclosure in the Notes to FS be undertaken to avoid discrepancies;
Refrain from charging in the LDRRMF the construction of open-air structures, instead, maximize the utilization of the fund for disaster risk reduction and management activities; and
Direct the Municipal Budget Officer to maintain separate RAAOs for LDRRMF to facilitate proper control and monitoring of appropriations, allotments and obligations under the said fund.

We recommended that the LCE, through the Municipal SWMB:
Fast track the revision of the SWMP and have it approved to ensure that PPAs included in the plan are in accordance with the National SWM Framework;
Encourage and provide needed assistance to the remaining 35 barangays to establish their own MRFs for the collection, segregation, recycling of biodegradable, recyclable, compostable and reusable wastes;
Allocate funds for the construction and operation of a sanitary landfill as a final disposal site for solid wastes; and
Coordinate with the source agency (DENR-EMB) to furnish the Municipality with the complete documentation of the transferred equipment and inquire/request for instruction or demonstration on its proper use and maintenance.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Municipal Planning and Development Coordinator (MPDC) to facilitate the gathering of data and information needed for the creation of an updated and well-established GAD database to have an accurate and reliable basis in the planning and programming of PPAs as well as in the policy formulation in order to properly address the existing and emerging GAD issues and concerns;
Direct the GFPS and GAD key personnel to undergo capacity building programs and training on gender and development to enhance their knowledge and build their competencies on GAD-related laws and international commitments, gender mainstreaming, gender analysis, gender-responsive planning and budgeting, and GAD-related tools like HGDG on the attributed budget to evaluate gender responsiveness of PPAs in the GAD Plan and Budget;
Ensure that the PPAs charged to GAD fund are only those that would address the identified gender issues in the locality. The gender issues must be specific and supported by evidence such as sex-disaggregated data and gender analysis results; and
Require the GFPS to update the GAD Code in accordance with the guidelines prescribed by PCW.

We recommended that Management:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to properly account for the acquisition and issuance of the supplies and materials inventory by adopting the Perpetual Inventory System and ensure that the JEVs in recording the Supplies and Materials Expenses are supported with complete documentation; 

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the SSMI to the Municipal Accountant together with the original copies of the RIS which will be the basis of the latter to record in the books the expended portions of supplies and materials;

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to conduct periodic physical count of all supplies and materials on hand, submit the required RPCI and coordinate with the Municipal Accountant to reconcile the same with the accounting records; and

Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to properly maintain, update and reconcile the stock cards and SLCs, respectively.

We recommended that Management:
Follow the Perpetual Inventory System in recording the payment for supplies and materials purchased by debiting the appropriate inventory account;
Require the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the SSMI to consolidate the supplies and materials issued from the RIS and submit the same to the Municipal Accountant;
Stop the practice of charging the inventories to appropriate expenditure accounts without proper and complete documentation. The Municipal Accountant must ensure that proper accounting entries are made, supported by the SSMI and the original copy of the RIS, to record issuance of supplies and materials;
Require the Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to maintain stock cards and SLCs, respectively, for all items of inventory. Periodic reconciliation of records must be undertaken to avoid misstatements in the quantity and amount of inventories; and
Conduct physical count of inventories semi-annually and prepare and submit the RCPI to the Auditor within the period prescribed.

We recommended that Management be more prudent in the utilization of its LDRRMF, taking into consideration the existing rules and regulations governing the utilization of the said fund and require the:
MDRRMO to submit the Monthly Report on Sources and Utilization of the DRRMF duly certified correct by the Municipal Accountant on or before the 15th day after the end of each month;
MDRRMO and Municipal Budget Officer to allocate funds for the repair and maintenance and insurance of the DRRM vehicle chargeable against Maintenance and Other Operating Expenses of the MDRRM Office;
MDRRMO to incorporate in the LDRRMFIP and utilize the LDRRMF for tangible projects and activities that will help build disaster resilient communities and enhance disaster preparedness and response capabilities of the Municipality; and
Municipal Accountant to ensure that relief distribution sheets and other proof of distribution are attached to the DVs covering the purchase of relief goods for distribution for verification of this Office.

We reiterated our recommendation that the LCE direct the:

Municipal Accountant to prepare SLs per bank account and give preferential attention on the preparation and submission of the BRSs pursuant to COA Circular No. 96-011;



Municipal Treasurer to maintain and regularly update the cash books and reflect the reconciling items per BRS, transfer the balance of the account maintained at PNB to an AGDB, and to close accounts that have become dormant and revert back to the Source Agency or the Bureau of the Treasury, as the case maybe.

We recommended that the Municipal Accountant:

Prepare an adjusting journal entry to correct the balances of Loans Payable and Government Equity, beginning, due to erroneous recording of principal payments and non-recording of GRT in the books;

Strengthen accounting controls over loans payable by reviewing thoroughly the amortization schedule given by the bank and carefully analyzing transaction before recording in the books and updating entries of both records.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:

Create a General Services Officer (GSO) position that will discharge on a full time basis the property custodianship functions and the receipt, issuance and recording of the procurement and issuance of supplies and property, maintain updated Property Cards per category on all property, plant and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant and Equipment of accounting records and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE;

Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;

Require both offices to reconcile and work out on tracing any resulting difference, establish its existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken; and

Maintain and renew all Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment every three years for the signature of the holder of each item listed in the prepared RPCPPE or based on the old Memorandum Receipts on file.

With the foregoing observations, we recommended to the management to:
a) Establish Inventory Committee that would spearhead the conduct of inventory count and
prepare the corresponding Report on the Physical Count of Inventories to be submitted to
the Accounting Office and COA Audit Team;
b) Require the Municipal Accountant to record all acquisitions of inventories at their proper
inventory accounts and should be expensed only once used/consumed;
c) Revisit current accounting practices and institute reforms to comply with the prescribed
accounting standards under International Public Sector Accounting Standards (IPSAS);
d) Devise a uniform system of procedure in the monitoring, controlling and recording of
acquisition and issuance of inventory.

We recommended to the management to direct the Municipal Accountant to:
a) Prepare correcting entries to fix the accounting errors made on the disposal of properties;
b) Reconstruct the Cash Flows Statements manually so that accurate and reliable information
are presented;
c) Check, verify and review transactions affecting the disposals and acquisitions of PPEs to
ensure proper presentation of accounts on the face of the FS;
d) Evaluate and revisit the electronic accounting system employed by the LGU to avoid
similar errors in the future.

