Create a General Services Officer (GSO) position that will discharge on a full time basis the property custodianship functions and the receipt, issuance and recording of the procurement and issuance of supplies and property, maintain updated Property Cards per category on all property, plant and equipment as recorded in the list of Property, Plant and Equipment of accounting records and facilitate the proper conduct of the physical count and preparation of the RPCPPE;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain property ledger cards consistent with their accounting records;
Require both offices to reconcile and work out on tracing any resulting difference, establish its existence/non-existence and determine from there any further action that may be undertaken; and
Maintain and renew all Acknowledgment Receipt for Equipment every three years for the signature of the holder of each item listed in the prepared RPCPPE or based on the old Memorandum Receipts on file.

We recommended for the local chief executive to:
1. Revisit, review and evaluate the programs/projects/activities included in the Annual Investment Plan of the 20% Economic Development Fund to ensure effective formulation, implementation and utilization of the Fund;
2. Ensure that all projects to be funded from the 20% Economic Development Fund shall partake the nature of investment or capital expenditure;
3. Adhere strictly with the provisions of DILG-DBM Joint Memorandum Circular Nos. 2011-1 and 2017-01 dated April 13, 2011 and February 22, 2017, repectively, to ensure that the 20% of the IRA is optimally utilized to help achieve desirable socio-economic development and environmental outcomes;
4. Submit the lacking documents and transactions enumerated in Annex B. Ensure 100% complete submission of accounts and transactions by the Municipality.

We recommend the Local Chief Executive to instruct the concerned official/personnel to:
Consolidate the PPMPs submitted by the end-user Offices;
Implement strictly timelines on the posting and submission of procurement reports;
Establish procurement timelines in consonance with project schedules, including a cut-off date for processing requisitions and issuance of purchase orders to ensure receipt of most of the procured items in time for the project implementation;
Consider the strict observance of RA 9184 and its IRR, and other existing rules and regulation on government procurement as well as imposition of control measures to ensure that procurement is effected in an efficient, economical and effective manner that is most advantageous to the government and to prevent possible disallowances for such violation.

Present the Logbook of daily attendances as required under Item 4. Section VI of the guidelines, duly signed by each worker;
Submit justification on why the cash advance was made by the Disbursing Officer and not by the MSWDO or the In Charge of Office;
Submit an explanation on why the fund was turned over to the Barangay Chairmen;
Submit/attach copy of the Assessment report submitted to the DSWD-FO containing justification/s for extending the number of days for the project to be accomplished.
Submit a copy of the Appointment Contracts bearing the signatures of the appointee.

We recommended that:

1. The Municipal Treasurer submit to the Accounting Office all the disbursement vouchers, official receipts including the corresponding reports of each month on or before the fifth day of the ensuing month;

2. The Municipal Accountant strictly comply with the timetable on the submission of accounts as required under existing laws, rules and regulations.
